  "text": "Electrostatic binding of nanoparticles to microbubbles is often implemented in gene delivery studies, wherein negatively charged dna is attached to positively charged microbubbles with shells composed of a cationic lipid. Electrostatic interactions can also be exploited to create nanoparticle-bound microbubbles. one example of this was described by seo et al. who created positively charged monodisperse microbubbles through microfluidics and attached negatively charged silica-coated nanoparticles [CITATION_1] . This technique was shown to be effective for various sizes and shapes of nanoparticles.",
